{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel0 \b \fs36 Introduction\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 At least eleven states have enacted laws against unauthorized photography, recording, or other data collection on private property.{\super\chftn}{\*\footnote\chftn\~\plain\pard {\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Animal Welfare Institute, {\i Anti-whistleblower (\u8220"Ag-Gag\u8221") Legislation}, {\scaps Animal Welfare Institute}, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://awionline.org/content/anti-whistleblower-legislation"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
https://awionline.org/content/anti-whistleblower-legislation
}}}
 (last visited Feb 27, 2023); Center for Constitutional Rights, Ag-Gag Across America: Corporate-Backed Attacks on Activitsts and Whistleblowers 10 (2017). States that have adopted such laws include (in chronological order): Kansas, Montana, North Dakota, Alabama, Iowa, Missouri, Utah, Idaho, Wyoming, North Carolina, and Arkansas. Center for Constitutional Rights, {\i supra} note 1 at 10, 13, 15\u8211-16, 18\u8211-20. The earliest of these laws applied specifically to agricultural facilities, giving rise to the sobriquet \u8220"ag-gag\u8221" laws. See Center for Constitutional Rights, {\i supra} note 1 at 2\u8211-3; Shaakirrah R. Sanders, {\i Ag-Gag Free Nation}, 54 {\scaps Wake Forest L. Rev.} 491, 493\u8211-94 (2019).\par}
} Among the most recent examples is the North Carolina Property Protection Act (\u8220"NCPPA\u8221").{\super\chftn}{\*\footnote\chftn\~\plain\pard {\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 N.C. Gen. Stat. \u167 ? 99A-2 (2016). Arkansas has adopted a similar statute. Ark. Code \u167 ? 16-118-113 (2017); see {\i Animal Legal Defense Fund v. Vaught}, No. 4:19cv00442, 4 (E.D. Ark. Feb. 14, 2020) (\u8220"Representative Vaught \u8230 ? explained in introducing the Arkansas Ag-Gag law to the House Judiciary Committee that it \u8216'is modeled after a newly enacted law in North Carolina in 2016.\u8217'\u8221").\par}
}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The NCPPA represents a new approach to state laws against data trespass,{\super\chftn}{\*\footnote\chftn\~\plain\pard {\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 I use the term \u8220"data trespass\u8221" to encompass laws imposing criminal or civil liability for unauthorized recording or data collection, whether limited to agricultural facilities or (as in North Carolina, Arkansas, and Wyoming) covering other premises and facilities as well. See Hannah Solomon, {\i Wyoming\u8217's Data Trespass Laws Trample First Amendment Rights: A Preview}, {\scaps Vermont Journal of Environmental Law: Ecoperspectives Blog} (2016), {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://vjel.vermontlaw.edu/wyomings-data-trespass-laws-trample-first-amendment-rights-preview"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
https://vjel.vermontlaw.edu/wyomings-data-trespass-laws-trample-first-amendment-rights-preview
}}}
 (last visited Mar 1, 2023) (describing Wyoming statutes as \u8220"data trespass laws\u8221"); Lauren Kurtz, {\i Wyoming Federal Court Upholds Law Criminalizing \u8220"Unlawful Collection of Resource Data\u8221"}, {\scaps Climate Law Blog} (2016), {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://blogs.law.columbia.edu/climatechange/2016/07/28/wy-federal-court-upholds-law-criminalizing-resource-data-collection/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
https://blogs.law.columbia.edu/climatechange/2016/07/28/wy-federal-court-upholds-law-criminalizing-resource-data-collection/
}}}
 (last visited Mar 1, 2023) (same).\par}
} differing from previous ag-gag laws in three significant respects. First, unlike laws limited to agricultural facilities, the NCPPA applies more broadly to any private property.{\super\chftn}{\*\footnote\chftn\~\plain\pard {\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 N.C. Gen. Stat. \u167 ? 99A-2. The Arkansas statute similarly prohibits unauthorized recording on \u8220"commercial property\u8221", which is defined to include any \u8220"business property\u8221", \u8220"Agricultural or timber production operations\u8221", and \u8220"Residential property used for business purposes\u8221". Ark. Code \u167 ? 16-118-113. Wyoming\u8217's resource data collection statutes also apply to any \u8220"private land\u8221", but their prohibitions are limited to unauthorized collection of \u8220"resource data\u8221" (defined as \u8220"data relating to land or land use, including but not limited to data regarding agriculture, minerals, geology, history, cultural artifacts, archeology, air, water, soil, conservation, habitat, vegetation or animal species\u8221"). Wyo. Stat. \u167 ? 6-3-414 (2015) (imposing criminal liability) and Wyo. Stat. \u167 ? 40-27-101 (2015) (establishing civil cause of action).\par}
} Second, while previous laws typically imposed criminal liability,{\super\chftn}{\*\footnote\chftn\~\plain\pard {\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 See Center for Constitutional Rights, {\i supra} note 1 at 6, 10\u8211-11, 14, 17\u8211-18.\par}
} the NCPPA creates a civil cause of action for acts exceeding the scope of authorized entry to the premises.{\super\chftn}{\*\footnote\chftn\~\plain\pard {\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 N.C. Gen. Stat. \u167 ? 99A-2; Ark. Code \u167 ? 16-118-113. Some other states\u8217' laws also authorize private civil actions by the owner or operator of the facility.\par}
} Third, the NCPPA specifically targets unauthorized recording and other data collection by employees.{\super\chftn}{\*\footnote\chftn\~\plain\pard {\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 N.C. Gen. Stat. \u167 ? 99A-2(b)(1)\u8211-(3); Ark. Code \u167 ? 16-118-113(c)(1)\u8211-(3). Some ag-gag statutes contain specific provisions aimed at so-called \u8220"employment fraud\u8221" for the purpose of gaining access to an agricultural facility. See, e.g., Idaho Code \u167 ? 18-7042 (2014) (imposing liability on one who \u8220"Obtains employment with an agricultural production facility by force, threat, or misrepresentation with the intent to cause economic or other injury\u8221"); Iowa Code \u167 ? 717A.3A (2012); Ala. Code \u167 ? 13A-11-150 (2002); see also Center for Constitutional Rights, {\i supra} note 1 at 2, 10\u8211-11.\par}
}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The focus of this article is on this last issue. At least some of the employee activity subject to civil liability under the NCPPA and other state data trespass laws{\super\chftn}{\*\footnote\chftn\~\plain\pard {\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 See Part 2.\par}
} is protected under the National Labor Relations Act (\u8220"NLRA\u8221"){\super\chftn}{\*\footnote\chftn\~\plain\pard {\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 29 U.S. Code \u167 ? 151 et seq. (1935).\par}
} and other federal laws.{\super\chftn}{\*\footnote\chftn\~\plain\pard {\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 See Part 3.\par}
} The Supremacy Clause dictates that this conflict must be resolved in favor of federal law under the preemption doctrine.{\super\chftn}{\*\footnote\chftn\~\plain\pard {\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 See Part 4.\par}
}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The NCPPA and other state data trespass statutes have faced legal challenges on constitutional grounds.{\super\chftn}{\*\footnote\chftn\~\plain\pard {\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\i Peta v. North Carolina Farm Bureau Federation}, (Court of Appeals, 4th Circuit Feb. 23, 2023) (North Carolina); {\i Animal Legal Defense Fund v. Vaught}, 8 F.4th 714 (8th Cir. 2021) (Arkansas); {\i Animal Legal Defense Fund v. Kelly}, 9 F.4th 1219 (10th Cir. 2021) (Kansas); {\i Animal Legal Defense Fund v. Reynolds}, 591 F. Supp. 3d 397 (S.D. Iowa 2022) (Iowa); {\i Animal Legal Defense Fund v. Wasden}, 878 F.3d 1184 (9th Cir. 2018) (Idaho); {\i Western Watersheds Project v. Michael}, 353 F. Supp. 3d 1176 (D. Wyo. 2018) (Wyoming); {\i Animal Legal Defense Fund v. Herbert}, 263 F. Supp. 3d 1193 (D. Utah 2017) (Utah).\par}
} However, the courts have not addressed the issue of federal preemption.{\super\chftn}{\*\footnote\chftn\~\plain\pard {\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 In at least two cases, labor organizations filed amicus briefs arguing that the imposition of employee liability under state ag-gag statutes would conflict with and undermine protections under federal labor and employment law. See United Farm Workers of America brief as amicus curiae in ALDF v. Wasden; Idaho Building Trades Council & Idaho AFL-CIO brief as amicus curiae in ALDF v. Wasden; United Farm Workers of America, brief as amicus curiae in ALDF v. Kelly; United Food & Commercial Workers International Union, brief as amicus curiae in ALDF v. Kelly. In {\i Kelly}, {\i supra} note 12, at n.6, the 10th Circuit explicitly declined to consider whether the Kansas ag-gag statute violated the NLRA, because the parties themselves had not presented the issue. In {\i ALDF v Wasden}, {\i supra} note 12, the 9th Circuit held that parts of the Idaho ag-gag statute violated the 1st Amendment, without mentioning federal labor preemption at all.\par}
} Existing scholarship on state data trespass laws has likewise focused primarily on the First Amendment and other constitutional problems, with little attention to the impairment of workers\u8217' rights under federal labor and employment law.{\super\chftn}{\*\footnote\chftn\~\plain\pard {\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 ONE PREVIOUS PIECE ON THE NCPPA; NUMEROUS ARTICLES ON AG-GAG. MOSTLY FOCUSED ON THE CONSTITUTIONAL ISSUES.\par}
}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 This article aims to address this gap. Focusing on the NCPPA because of its explicit targeting of employee activity, it offers guidance to courts in recognizing and avoiding conflicts between employee liability under state data trespass laws and employee protections under the National Labor Relations Act and other federal labor law. To ensure that the prospect of costly litigation and damages does not penalize employees for, or deter them from, exercising their rights under federal law, I argue that preemption should apply to any state data trespass claims against employees who make recordings or otherwise collect information in the workplace pertaining to their terms and conditions of employment.\par}
