{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel0 \b \fs36 The NCPPA and Other State Data Trespass Laws Subject Employees to Liability for Conduct that is Protected Under Federal Labor Law\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The NCPPA expressly targets employee activity.{\super\chftn}{\*\footnote\chftn\~\plain\pard {\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 N.C. Gen. Stat. \u167 ? 99A-2; see also, Ark. Code \u167 ? 16-118-113. Some Ag-Gag statutes also specifically apply to employee activity. CITES. Others would implicitly apply to employees engaged in the types of activity generally subject to liability. CITES.\par}
} Most notably, this includes unauthorized recording or other data collection on the employer\u8217's premises. It may also include union \u8220"salting\u8221", communicating with co-workers and the public about working conditions, and providing information and evidence about possible legal violations to federal agencies. These activities are (at least in some circumstances) protected under federal labor law.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 As a threshold matter, the protections of federal labor law apply only to those who fit within the statutory definition of an employee. Certain categories of employees are excluded from coverage, notably agricultural laborers.{\super\chftn}{\*\footnote\chftn\~\plain\pard {\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 29 U.S. Code \u167 ? 152(3).\par}
} While this exclusion might appear to alleviate any conflict with state laws that apply only to agricultural facilities, that is not necessarily the case. The agricultural laborer exclusion applies only to those engaged directly in farming,{\super\chftn}{\*\footnote\chftn\~\plain\pard {\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\i Bud Antle, Inc. v. Barbosa}, 45 F.3d 1261, 1274 (9th Cir. 1994), (quoting {\i Camsco Produce Co.}, 297 N.L.R.B. 905 (N.L.R.B. 1990)).\par}
} or who \u8220"perform tasks which are incidental to or in conjunction with [the employer\u8217's] farming operations,\u8221"{\super\chftn}{\*\footnote\chftn\~\plain\pard {\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\i Bud Antle, Inc.}, {\i supra} note 3.\par}
} such as \u8220"processing agricultural products \u8230 ? grown on the premises of the farm itself.\u8221"{\super\chftn}{\*\footnote\chftn\~\plain\pard {\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\i NLRB v. Cal-Maine Farms, Inc.}, 998 F.2d 1336 (5th Circuit 1993).\par}
} However, it does not apply to those who are not employed by a \u8220"farmer\u8221",{\super\chftn}{\*\footnote\chftn\~\plain\pard {\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 See {\i Bud Antle, Inc.}, {\i supra} note 3 at 1274 (agricultural laborer exclusion does not apply to employees of vegetable cooling and packing facility where employer did not grow vegetables itself but purchased them from independent growers); {\i NLRB v. Monterey County B. & C. Trades Council}, 335 F.2d 927 (9th Circuit 1953) (agricultural laborer exclusion does not apply to employees of contractor hired to construct buildings and install equipment on poultry farm).\par}
} nor to those who process, distribute, or otherwise handle agricultural goods not grown or raised by the employer for use in its own farming operations.{\super\chftn}{\*\footnote\chftn\~\plain\pard {\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\i Holly Farms Corp. v. NLRB}, 517 U.S. 392 (U.S. 1966) (employees who collect live chickens from independent growers and deliver them to employer\u8217's processing plant not excluded); {\i Bayside Enterprises, Inc. v. NLRB}, 429 U.S. 298 (U.S. 1977) (truck drivers who deliver poultry feed produced at employer\u8217's mill to independent poultry farms under contract with employer not excluded); {\i NLRB v. Cal-Maine Farms, Inc.}, {\i supra} note 5 (egg processing facility employees who regularly handle products purchased by employer from outside sources not excluded); {\i Camsco Produce Co.}, {\i supra} note 3 (mushroom processing facility employees who regularly handle products purchased by employer from outside sources not excluded).\par}
}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 In contrast, ag-gag laws define agricultural facilities more broadly, to include not just farms but also other operations along the production, processing, and distribution chain.{\super\chftn}{\*\footnote\chftn\~\plain\pard {\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 See, e.g. Idaho Code \u167 ? 18-7042(2)(a) & (b) (defining \u8220"Agricultural production\u8221" and \u8220"Agricultural production facility\u8221" to include \u8220"Construction, expansion, use, maintenance and repair of an agricultural production facility,\u8221" \u8220"Processing and packaging agricultural products, including the processing and packaging of agricultural products into food and other agricultural commodities,\u8221" and \u8220"Manufacturing animal feed,\u8221" along with activity more directly connected to raising crops and animals.); accord OTHER STATES.\par}
} Consequently, the NLRA applies to at least some employees of agricultural facilities covered by state ag-gag laws.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel1 \b \fs32 Protected Activity Under the NLRA\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Section 7 of the NLRA \u8220"protect[s] the right of workers to act together to better their working conditions\u8221":{\super\chftn}{\*\footnote\chftn\~\plain\pard {\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\i NLRB v. Washington Aluminum Co.}, 370 U.S. 9 (U.S. 1962).\par}
}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li720 \fi0 Employees shall have the right to self-organization, to form, join, or assist labor organizations, to bargain collectively through representatives of their own choosing, and to engage in other concerted activities for the purpose of collective bargaining or other mutual aid or protection \u8230 ?.{\super\chftn}{\*\footnote\chftn\~\plain\pard {\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 29 U.S. Code \u167 ? 157.\par}
}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 It is an unfair labor practice under Section 8(a)(1) for an employer \u8220"to interfere with, restrain, or coerce employees in the exercise of the rights guaranteed in section 7\u8221".{\super\chftn}{\*\footnote\chftn\~\plain\pard {\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\i Id.} \u167 ? 151 et seq.158(a)(1).\par}
}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Concerted activity pertaining to \u8220"terms, tenure or conditions of employment\u8221"{\super\chftn}{\*\footnote\chftn\~\plain\pard {\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\i Washington Aluminum}, {\i supra} note 9, (quoting NLRA Section 2(9), 29 U.S.C. sec.\u160 ?152(a), defining \u8220"labor dispute\u8221").\par}
} is protected under Section 7 regardless of whether employees have organized or are seeking to organize in a labor union, and even absent \u8220"a specific demand upon their employer to remedy a condition they find objectionable\u8221".{\super\chftn}{\*\footnote\chftn\~\plain\pard {\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\i Washington Aluminum}, {\i supra} note 9.\par}
} Activity aimed at protecting the rights or advancing the interests of multiple employees is \u8220"concerted\u8221" for purposes of Section 7, even if undertaken by a single employee acting alone.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li720 \fi0 Nor can we accept the company\u8217's contention that because it admittedly had an established plant rule which forbade employees to leave their work without permission of the foreman, there was justifiable \u8220"cause\u8221" for discharging these employees, wholly separate and apart from any concerted activities in which they engaged in protest against the poorly heated plant. Section 10(c) of the Act does authorize an employer to discharge employees for \u8220"cause\u8221" and our cases have long recognized this right on the part of an employer. But this, of course, cannot mean that an employer is at liberty to punish a man by discharging him for engaging in concerted activities which \u167 ? 7 of the Act protects.{\super\chftn}{\*\footnote\chftn\~\plain\pard {\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\i Washington Aluminum}, {\i supra} note 9.\par}
}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Under current Board law, an employer\u8217's facially neutral work rule that might apply to some protected Section 7 activity does not necessarily violate Section 8(a)(1).{\super\chftn}{\*\footnote\chftn\~\plain\pard {\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\i The Boeing Company}, 365 N.L.R.B. No. 154 (N.L.R.B. 2017).\par}
} However, it is an unfair labor practice for an employer to enforce such a rule against an employee for conduct protected under Section 7.{\super\chftn}{\*\footnote\chftn\~\plain\pard {\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\i AT&T Mobility, LLC}, 370 N.L.R.B. No. 121 (N.L.R.B. 2021) (employer\u8217's facially neutral work rule against workplace recording was lawful under NLRA; but employee\u8217's recording of disciplinary meeting, in violation of work rule, was protected under Section 7, and employer committed unfair labor practice by threatening employee with reprisals for future violations of the rule)\par}
}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Recording & Other Data Collection\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Section 7 protects employees who take photographs, make audio or video recordings, or use other means to collect information about workplace conditions, communications, or activity for the purpose of mutual aid and protection.{\super\chftn}{\*\footnote\chftn\~\plain\pard {\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\i White Oak Manor}, 353 N.L.R.B. 795, 798\u8211-99, n.2 (N.L.R.B. 2009) (finding that photography was part of the {\i res gestae} of employee\u8217's protected concerted activity in documenting inconsistent enforcement of employer dress code); {\i Sullivan, Long & Hagerty}, 303 N.L.R.B. 1007, 1013 (N.L.R.B. 1991) (finding employee\u8217's use of tape recorder in workplace to aid federal government investigation to be protected).\par}
} Employees may also use \u8220"surreptitious\u8221" or otherwise unauthorized recordings as evidence in administrative or judicial proceedings to vindicate their legal rights.{\super\chftn}{\*\footnote\chftn\~\plain\pard {\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\i Whole Foods Market, Inc.}, 363 N.L.R.B. No. 87 (N.L.R.B. 2015), citing {\i Times-Herald Record}, 334 N.L.R.B. 350, 354 (N.L.R.B. 2001); {\i Arrow Flint Electric Co.}, 321 N.L.R.B. 1208, 1219 (N.L.R.B. 1996); {\i Wellstream Corp.}, 313 N.L.R.B. 698, 711 (N.L.R.B. 1994); {\i McAllister Bros.}, 278 N.L.R.B. 601, 601 (N.L.R.B. 1986), n.\u160 ?2, 605, n.3; {\i Algreco Sportswear Co.}, 271 N.L.R.B. 499, 505 (N.L.R.B. 1984); {\i East Belden Corp.}, 239 N.L.R.B. 776, 782 (N.L.R.B. 1978).\par}
}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Employees are subject to liability under the NCPPA for recording or data collection in the non-public areas of the workplace \u8220"without authorization\u8221". It is unclear whether \u8220"without authorization\u8221" simply means that the employee violates an employer\u8217's rule prohibiting or restricting such activity, or if it means the employee must obtain the employer\u8217's affirmative permission even where there is no general anti-recording rule in place. Either way, there is a conflict with the protection that the NLRA extends to employees who make recordings or otherwise collect information in the workplace in the exercise of their rights under Section 7.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Salting\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The NCPPA imposes liability on unauthorized data collection or recording by \u8220"An employee who enters the nonpublic areas of an employer\u8217's premises {\i for a reason other than a bona fide intent of seeking or holding employment} or doing business with the employer.\u8221"{\super\chftn}{\*\footnote\chftn\~\plain\pard {\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 N.C. Gen. Stat. \u167 ? 99A-2(b)(1) & (2) (emphasis supplied); see also Ark. Code \u167 ? 16-118-113. Some Ag-Gag laws similarly target those who gain entry to the premises under the guise of seeking employment. See, e.g., CITE (imposing liability on one who \u8220"Obtains employment with an agricultural production facility by force, threat, or misrepresentation with the intent to cause economic or other injury\u8221").\par}
}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 This provision could be construed to apply to union \u8220"salts\u8221": union members who take jobs at non-union workplaces with the aim of organizing the employees.{\super\chftn}{\*\footnote\chftn\~\plain\pard {\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 See Carey Dall & Jonathan Cohen, {\i Salting the Earth: Organizing for the Long Haul}, {\scaps New Labor Forum} 36 (2002); Erik Forman, {\i Let\u8217's Get to Work}, {\scaps Jacobin} (2017), {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://jacobinmag.com/2017/02/labor-unions-workers-salts-students-organizing/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
http://jacobinmag.com/2017/02/labor-unions-workers-salts-students-organizing/
}}}
 (reviewing the history and practice of salting and describing the author\u8217's own experience as a salt); James D. Walsh, {\i The Double Life of an Undercover Union Organizer}, {\scaps New York Magazine Intelligencer} (2016), {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://nymag.com/intelligencer/2016/02/what-its-like-tobea-salt-for-the-unions.html"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
http://nymag.com/intelligencer/2016/02/what-its-like-tobea-salt-for-the-unions.html
}}}
.\par}
} Salts sometimes identify themselves as union members and organizers when applying for jobs,{\super\chftn}{\*\footnote\chftn\~\plain\pard {\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 See, e.g., {\i Aerotek, Inc. v. N.L.R.B.}, 883 F.3d 725 (8th Cir. 2018); {\i Fluor Daniel, Inc.}, 311 N.L.R.B. 498 (N.L.R.B. 1993).\par}
} but sometimes keep their affiliation and motive covert.{\super\chftn}{\*\footnote\chftn\~\plain\pard {\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 See, e.g., Bourree Lam, {\i Life as an Undercover Union Organizer}, {\scaps The Atlantic} (2016), {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.theatlantic.com/business/archive/2016/03/undercover-union-organizer/474387/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
https://www.theatlantic.com/business/archive/2016/03/undercover-union-organizer/474387/
}}}
 (describing experience as a covert salt).\par}
} In the latter circumstance, the employer may very well regard the concealment as a misrepresentation. Employers wishing to avoid unions no doubt regard salting as harmful to their economic interests.{\super\chftn}{\*\footnote\chftn\~\plain\pard {\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The view that salting is a devious practice causing economic harm to employers is reflected in a congressional hearing on alleged \u8220"salting abuses\u8221". {\i Examining Union \u8220"Salting\u8221" Abuses and Organizing Tactics That Harm the U.S. Economy: Hearing before the Subcomm. on Employer-Employee Relations of the H. Comm. on Education and the Workforce}, 108th Cong. (2004). In his opening statement, subcommittee chair Rep.\u160 ?Sam Johnson contended that \u8220"Certain unions use \u8216'salts\u8217' to cause deliberate harm to businesses by increasing their costs and forcing them to spend time, energy, and money to defend themselves against frivolous charges, and sometimes, to run employers out of business.\u8221" Examining Union Salting Abuses, {\i Id.} at 2. A parade of employer witnesses then gave anguished testimony about the alleged harms they suffered as a result of salting campaigns. Examining Union Salting Abuses, {\i Id.} at x. In similar vein, a \u8220"Fact Sheet\u8221" in support of proposed legislation to outlaw salting, issued by a prominent anti-union organization, decried the practice as \u8220"an organized conspiracy on the part of Big Labor bosses\u8221" and \u8220"an instrument of economic destruction aimed at non-union companies\u8221". National Right to Work Committee, Salting: Coercive Big Labor Scheme to Increase Forced Unionism (2003). See also, Nick Johnson, {\i No Salt Added}, {\scaps Jacobin} (2017), {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://jacobinmag.com/2017/03/salts-union-organizing-nlrb-obama-trump-labor"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
http://jacobinmag.com/2017/03/salts-union-organizing-nlrb-obama-trump-labor
}}}
 (discussing legislative efforts to reverse Town & Country and outlaw salting); CURRENT ANTI-SALTING BILL.\par}
}\par}
