}, whether overt or covert,{\super\chftn}{\*\footnote\chftn\~\plain\pard {\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 CITES\par}
} as long as they are \u8220"genuinely interested in seeking to establish an employment relationship with the employer.\u8221"{\super\chftn}{\*\footnote\chftn\~\plain\pard {\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\i Toering Electric Co.}, 351 N.L.R.B. 225 (N.L.R.B. 2007); {\i Oil Capitol Sheet Metal, Inc.}, 349 N.L.R.B. 1348 (N.L.R.B. 2007); see also Johnson, {\i supra} note 23 (discussing narrowed protection for salts under {\i Toering Electric} and Oil {\i Capitol Sheet Metal}).\par}
}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 MIGHT BE OK IF LIABILITY UNDER NCPPA & OTHER STATE LAWS IS LIMITED TO THOSE WHO OBTAIN EMPLOYMENT FOR THE SOLE PURPOSE OF CAUSING INJURY, OR WITH NO Bona Fide INTEREST IN THE JOB ITSELF. NOTE AMBIGUITY IN LANGUAGE OF NCPPA.{\super\chftn}{\*\footnote\chftn\~\plain\pard {\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 There might still be problems in relation to other federal employment laws. For example, the use of \u8220"tester\u8221" applicants is a common practice for identifying discriminatory hiring practices. CITES. Courts have upheld the practice even where the testers had no real interest in the job. CITES.\par}
} But, as written, \u8220"employment fraud\u8221" provisions in these statutes at least plausibly cover those with mixed motives, who would be regarded as statutory employees under the NLRA. This is particularly true of the NCPPA, which explicitly identifies those subject to liability as \u8220"employees\u8221" and further predicates their liability on the use of recordings or other information \u8220"to breach the person\u8217's duty of loyalty to the employer.\u8221"\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Communication with Co-Workers & Public\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Employees under the NLRA also have a right to communicate with co-workers and the public about working conditions and disputes.{\super\chftn}{\*\footnote\chftn\~\plain\pard {\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\i Kinder-Care Learning Centers, Inc.}, 299 N.L.R.B. 1171 (N.L.R.B. 1990).\par}
}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Providing Information and Evidence to Federal Agencies\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The NLRA protects the right of employees to petition for a union representation election, file complaints of unfair labor practices with the NLRB, and testify at NLRB proceedings.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 By impairing the ability of employees to document workplace conditions and activity, the NCPPA undermines the NLRB\u8217's procedures for vindicating employee\u8217's rights under the NLRA.{\super\chftn}{\*\footnote\chftn\~\plain\pard {\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The NCPPA and other data trespass laws similarly undermine the enforcement of other federal laws that protect employees against health and safety hazards, discrimination, wage theft, and other harmful and abusive employment practices, Employers are hardly likely to grant employees permission to collect evidence of such violations, and may very well attempt to cover up the problems if alerted that employees are planning to do so. Consequently, to substantiate claims of unlawful working conditions or employer conduct, employees must frequently take photos, make audio-video recordings, or copy documents without the employer\u8217's knowledge and consent. See United Farm Workers Amicus Brief.\par}
}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Disclosure of information to state officials is exempt from liability under the NCPPA. However, the statute contains no exemption for disclosures to federal agencies or officials.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel1 \b \fs32 Disloyalty Under the NLRA\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Concerted activity may lose protection under the NLRA if it amounts to disloyalty to the employer. For example, \u8220"sharp, public, disparaging attack[s] upon the quality of the company\u8217's product and its business policies, in a manner reasonably calculated to harm the company\u8217's reputation and reduce its income\u8221" may be unprotected, even if made in connection with a labor dispute.{\super\chftn}{\*\footnote\chftn\~\plain\pard {\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\i NLRB v. Electrical Workers}, 346 U.S. 464 (U.S. 1953) (affirming NLRB decision that employees\u8217' distribution of handbills attacking quality of employer\u8217's television programming, without reference to labor dispute, was unprotected); {\i Miklin Enterprises, Inc. v. NLRB}, (8th Circuit Submitted: September 19, 2016) (holding statements by union supporters in posters and press releases, suggesting employer\u8217's customers faced health risk from eating food prepared by employees working while sick, were unprotected even though related to employees\u8217' effort to gain paid sick leave).\par}
}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 COMPARE/CONTRAST DISLOYALTY EXCEPTION UNDER NLRA WITH \u8220"DUTY OF LOYALTY\u8221" UNDER STATE LAW.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel0 \b \fs36 Federal Law Preempts the NCPPA and Other State Data Trespass Laws to the Extent that They Impose Liability on Employees for Conduct Protected Under the National Labor Relations Act\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel1 \b \fs32 NLRA Preemption\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Scope of Preemption\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The preemptive sweep of federal labor law is particularly broad:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li720 \fi0 When it is clear or may fairly be assumed that the activities which a State purports to regulate are protected by \u167 ? 7 of the National Labor Relations Act, or constitute an unfair labor practice under \u167 ? 8, due regard for the federal enactment requires that state jurisdiction must yield. To leave the States free to regulate conduct so plainly within the central aim of federal regulation involves too great a danger of conflict between power asserted by Congress and requirements imposed by state law.{\super\chftn}{\*\footnote\chftn\~\plain\pard {\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\i San Diego Building Trades Council v. Garmon}, 359 U.S. 236, 244 (U.S. 1959). Federal law may also preempt state regulation of \u8220"conduct neither protected by \u167 ? 7 nor prohibited by \u167 ? 8,\u8221" where \u8220"Congress intended [it] to be \u8216'unrestricted by Any governmental power to regulate\u8217' because it was among the permissible \u8216'economic weapons in reserve, . . . actual exercise (of which) on occasion by the parties, is part and parcel of the system that the Wagner and Taft-Hartley Acts have recognized.\u8217'\u8221" {\i Machinists v. Wisconsin Employment Relations Commission}, 427 U.S. 132, 141 (U.S. 1976) (citation omitted)\par}
}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li720 \fi0 If employee conduct is protected under \u167 ? 7, then state law which interferes with the exercise of these federally protected rights creates an actual conflict and is preempted by direct operation of the Supremacy Clause.{\super\chftn}{\*\footnote\chftn\~\plain\pard {\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\i Brown v. Hotel and Restaurant Employees and Bartenders Intern. Union Local 54}, 468 US 491, 501 (U.S. 1984).\par}
}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 BASIS OF PREEMPTION: Protect national labor policy and preserve NLRB\u8217's exclusive original jurisdiction over labor disputes.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li720 \fi0 Cases that have held state authority to be preempted by federal law tend to fall into one of two categories: (1) those that reflect the concern that \u8220"one forum would enjoin, as illegal, conduct which the other forum would find legal\u8221" and (2) those that reflect the concern \u8220"that the (application of state law by) state courts would restrict the exercise of rights guaranteed by the Federal Acts.\u8221" \u8220"(I)n referring to decisions holding state laws preempted by the NLRA, care must be taken to distinguish pre-emption based on federal protection of the conduct in question . . . from that based predominantly on the primary jurisdiction of the National Labor Relations Board . . ., although the two are often not easily separable.\u8221"{\super\chftn}{\*\footnote\chftn\~\plain\pard {\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\i Machinists v. Wisconsin Employment Relations Commission}, {\i supra} note 1 at 138 (citations omitted).\par}
}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \u8220"Local interests\u8221" exception under Garmon.{\super\chftn}{\*\footnote\chftn\~\plain\pard {\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\i Garmon}, {\i supra} note 1 at 243\u8211-44.\par}
}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li720 \fi0 If the state law regulates conduct that is actually protected by federal law, however, preemption follows not as a matter of protecting primary jurisdiction, but as a matter of substantive right. Where, as here, the issue is one of an asserted substantive conflict with a federal enactment, then \u8220"[t] he relative importance to the State of its own law is not material \u8230 ? for the Framers of our Constitution provided that the federal law must prevail.\u8221"{\super\chftn}{\*\footnote\chftn\~\plain\pard {\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\i Brown v. Hotel and Restaurant Employees and Bartenders Intern. Union Local 54}, {\i supra} note 2 at 503 (citation omitted).\par}
}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Why it doesn\u8217't apply to NCPPA.{\super\chftn}{\*\footnote\chftn\~\plain\pard }\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Accordingly, if an employer sues an employee under the NCPPA or other state data trespass law, based on workplace recording or other conduct arguably protected under the NLRA, the claim will be preempted.{\super\chftn}{\*\footnote\chftn\~\plain\pard {\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 See Part X, supra\par}
} A state court may not decide whether the conduct is indeed protected, as that question is within the exclusive original jurisdiction of the NLRB.{\super\chftn}{\*\footnote\chftn\~\plain\pard } Rather, as long as there is any colorable argument for NLRA protection, the state court should dismiss (or stay its proceedings pending a decision by the NLRB).{\super\chftn}{\*\footnote\chftn\~\plain\pard }\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 Procedure for Asserting Preemption\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \u8220"A claim of Garmon preemption is a claim that the state court has no power to adjudicate the subject matter of the case, and when a claim of Garmon preemption is raised, it must be considered and resolved by the state court.\u8221"{\super\chftn}{\*\footnote\chftn\~\plain\pard {\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 International Longshoremen\u8217's Ass\u8217'n.\u160 ?v. Davis, 476 US 380, 393 (1986)\par}
} Federal courts also lack subject matter jurisdiction over claims within the NLRB\u8217's primary jurisdiction.[^preemption5a] Accordingly, Garmon preemption is not a basis for removal.{\super\chftn}{\*\footnote\chftn\~\plain\pard {\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\i Bud Antle, Inc.}, {\i supra} note 3.\par}
} But, since Garmon preemption is a question of federal law, \u8220"if the state court errs in determining whether Garmon principles deprive it of jurisdiction over a dispute, review of that decision may be had in the Supreme Court.\u8221"{\super\chftn}{\*\footnote\chftn\~\plain\pard {\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\i Bud Antle, Inc.}, {\i supra} note 3 at 1269, quoting Ethridge v. Harbor House Restaurant, 861 F. 2d 1389, 1399 (1988)\par}
}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 However, the employee may obtain more immediate relief from the NLRB or a federal court. It is an unfair labor practice for an employer to maintain a preempted suit against an employee or union for protected concerted activity. {\super\chftn}{\*\footnote\chftn\~\plain\pard {\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\i Can-Am Plumbing, Inc. v. NLRB}, 321 F.3d 145, 151 (D.C. Cir. 2003); {\i Associated Building Contractors, Inc.}, 331 N.L.R.B. 132 (N.L.R.B. 2000); {\i Manno Elec., Inc.}, 321 N.L.R.B. 297 (N.L.R.B. 1996).\par}
} Accordingly, an employee faced with such a suit may file an unfair labor practice charge with the NLRB, which may then order the employer to seek dismissal or a stay (pending the NLRB\u8217's disposition of the unfair labor practice charge) of the state court action.{\super\chftn}{\*\footnote\chftn\~\plain\pard } The NLRB may also bring an action in a federal district court seeking an injunction for that purpose.{\super\chftn}{\*\footnote\chftn\~\plain\pard {\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\i Can-Am Plumbing, Inc. v. NLRB}, {\i supra} note 14 at 151, citing {\i Bill Johnson\u8217's Restaurants, Inc. v. NLRB}, 461 U.S. 731, 744 (U.S. 1983); {\i NLRB v. Nash-Finch Co.}, 404 U.S. 138, 144 (U.S. 1971).\par}
}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Alternatively, the employee may bring an action in federal court seeking declaratory and injunctive relief to block the state court action.{\super\chftn}{\*\footnote\chftn\~\plain\pard {\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 {\i Bud Antle, Inc.}, {\i supra} note 3 (holding employer may obtain declaratory and injunctive relief in federal court against pending state administrative agency proceeding).\par}
} BUT DO THE ANTI-INJUNCTION ACT OR YOUNGER ABSTENTION APPLY WHERE A PRIVATE PARTY SEEKS TO ENJOIN A PREEMPTED STATE COURT SUIT, RATHER THAN A STATE ADMINISTRATIVE PROCEEDING (AS IN Bud Antle)?\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel1 \b \fs32 Preemption Under Other Federal Employment Laws\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Admissibility in agency actions and employee suits of recordings made or evidence otherwise collected without the employer\u8217's permission. The Wyoming statutes state that data collected in violation of those statutes is inadmissible in any proceeding. ANY OTHER AG-GAG STATUTES HAVE SIMILAR PROVISIONS? Even without such an explicit exlusionary provision, other ag-gag and data trespass statutes would have the practical effect of deterring employees from using unauthorized workplace recordings as evidence of employment law violations and subjecting them to criminal or civil liability for doing so.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel0 \b \fs36 Conclusion\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Courts should dismiss suits on pre-emption grounds. The NLRB should seek injunctive relief and hold employers liable for unfair labor practices, consistent with established law. Legislatures should stop writing statutes that are illegal.\par}
